				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Newbie here!<a name="36141"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 23 04 11:42 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Surion, 
<br />
   Welcome!
<br />
    You are not alone in your frustrations, and it will not end at level 20, 30, 40, 50 or even 60, because people LOVE to break mezzes. I have found that hotkeys help a lot (Ex &quot;&lt;---MEZZING %t You break it you tank it my friend!!-----&gt;&quot;.) Spam that one a few times and make sure that you tell the group to assist the tank and not you, because you will be switching targets to mezz and this can confuse people. Ask the tank to assist you as soon as you hit your INC message and tell them never to switch targets unless you call for it, I've also found that the more space between you and the group while you pull, the better. Say you pull 3 by accident that all have the same name, with distance between you and the group you can mezz 2 on the run and take one back, hit your INC message and sick them on it, then when the other two mezzes break and the adds come running in, you should be ready to mez them while the rest of the group concentrates on the single. I personally feel that while I'm pulling, I'm running the show, and I make that known by -Politely- telling people what to do. Dealing with difficult people is probably the hardest part about being a bard (in my opinion) so be patient and always be pleasant, people remember that sort of thing and no one wants a bossy bard yelling at them.
<br />
   Another tip you may find helpful, if you want some great places to practice lulling around lvl 15, go to blackburrow and try to pull singles out of the base of the elite ledge with lull, or the green room by the spike pit, it's full of elites and can get you great xp and is a tricky spot to pull singles because they are packed in and you have to -just barely- peek around the corner for the lull. If you are having a hard time with seeing mobs before you come around corners, use the F9 key to switch views and rotate the camera to look right around the corner. 
<br />
   Remember that you don't need a line of sight in order to use bard lulls, and as soon as you start it you can switch targets and it will still lull the original target unless you stop the song. This means that you can use the camera to switch views, toss on a lull or two, then switch targets and pull with snare or bellow and as soon as you start the pull song, you can run around a corner to have a bit of control over which way the mob runs. You only need Line of Sight when the song starts on any song besides lull, which doesn't need any Line of Sight. 
<br />

<br />
Anyways some rambling, I hope it helps. Pulling is my favorite thing about being a bard and it's only going to get more fun, so I hope I can help you when you need it, I'll keep an eye on this thread.
<br />
 <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /></span></td>
