				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Newbie here!<a name="36146"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 23 04 11:49 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>What you are describing is typical newbish stuff.  At your tender age, it is only costing you a little extra downtime.  At higher levels, failure to /assist (I'll explain below) will get you all killed!
<br />

<br />
The solution to the problem is the /assist command.  It can be typed, or set up on a macro.  There are two main ways to do it.
<br />

<br />
1)  Target your main tank (click on them, or their HP bar) and type /assist.  Now your auto-attack is on, and your target is the same as your Main Tank's target.
<br />

<br />
2)  Type /assist <i>player_name</i>.
<br />

<br />
If everyone in the group does this, then everyone will be smacking the same mob, and won't wake up your mezzes.  (Also, make sure you are not singing your Area of Effect damage songs, like Chords of Dissonance!)
<br />

<br />
You can also make a macro for /assist, and edit it each time you get a new group, or your main tank changes.  For info on creating macros, see <a href="http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=72&amp;ForumID=132">This guide</a> or <a href="http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=71&amp;ForumID=132">This guide</a>.
<br />

<br />
But your friends really SHOULD learn to /assist, and learn it soon.  It's already reducing your fun-factor a bit by creating more downtime (which would be true with a healer too, cause they would have to med more to get mana from healing more than necessary).  You fun-factor will REALLY be reduced when people start getting killed!
<br />

<br />
EDIT:  You also might find <a href="http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=70&amp;ForumID=132">Miabell's Tutelage:  An EQ Newbie Learns Barding</a> to be a helpful read.  Miabell, like you, was brand new to EQ.  This guide was copied from a thread like this one on the old eqdiva boards.  She returned many times with lots of good questions.</span></td>
