				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Newbie here!<a name="36201"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 23 04 2:56 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>When you lull it does have the chance to fail. Klapton's guide explains most of the details on beginner's pulling, try to be aware of aggro ranges and learn where that invisible circle is, because you don't want to step inside it. Different mobs do have different aggro ranges but once you get a baseline established for yourself you shouldn't have too much trouble as long as you're careful. Take your time, you'll learn how to pull faster later, trust me. 
<br />
When lulling here's a few things I hope will help:
<br />

<br />
1. Am I too close? 
<br />
(stay out of the lull song's range and keep casting it and moving closer until you find the maximum range, that's a good way to get used to it.)
<br />
2. Are all of the mobs by my target going to need lulling? How do I know which ones?
<br />
Generally, at first, you should lull everything you think is close enough to aggro when you pull the target, until you get more adjusted to the ranges. Target the mobs around your target, then start singing the lull, wait for it to complete casting before you start more lulls. As Klapton's guide says, there IS a chance your lull can fail. If that happens, 1 of 2 things will occur, the mob can aggro and bring everything else near it that is not lulled, or it might just stand there and do nothing, giving you a second chance to lull it. If you fail a lull you will get a red message telling you just that. Here's a crappily mapped example:
<br />

<br />
X=Other mobs
<br />
T=Your Target
<br />
Y=You
<br />

<br />
------X----
<br />
----T-------Y
<br />
------X-----
<br />

<br />
If you can understand the diagram above, it shows 2 extra mobs standing by or in front of your target. Target the right or left one, start the lull, wait for it to finish then target the opposite one and do the same. Once they have both been lulled, target the middle guy (your target) and fire up bellow or snare or whatever you prefer to use and bring him to your group by himself. The other two will not come unless you pull your target directly through them.
<br />
3. Does it matter which ones I lull/pull first?
<br />
Yes and no. Some people like to pull strong to weak, or vice versa, some folks make sure casters get pulled last because they tend to stand in one spot and cast instead of running after you. These little things are going to come from experience, a lot of it. Pulling is so much fun and learning it can be frustrating at times, just don't rush yourself. 
<br />
Hope this helped.
<br />

<br />
What server are you on?
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
